# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: platform-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In cognitive psychology, **cognitive load** is the effort being used in the working memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] However, over the years, the additivity of these types of cognitive load has been investigated and questioned.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Now it is believed that they circularly influence each other.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Cognitive load theory was developed in the late 1980s out of a study of problem solving by John Sweller.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Sweller argued that instructional design can be used to reduce cognitive load in learners.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Much later, other researchers developed a way to measure perceived mental effort which is indicative of cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Task-invoked pupillary response is a reliable and sensitive measurement of cognitive load that is directly related to working memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Much information, such as Declarative knowledge, may only be stored in long-term memory after first being attended to, and processed by, working memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This was originally thought to be true for all long-term memory under the classic "gateway" model of the Atkinson–Shiffrin memory model.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] However, modern research has shown that some long-term memory can be encoded while bypassing, or working in parallel with, working memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Working memory, however, is extremely limited in both capacity and duration.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] These limitations will, under some conditions, impede learning.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Heavy cognitive load can have negative effects on task completion, and the experience of cognitive load is not the same in everyone.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The elderly, students, and children experience different, and more often higher, amounts of cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The fundamental tenet of cognitive load theory is that the quality of instructional design will be raised if greater consideration is given to the role and limitations of working memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] With increased distractions, particularly from the rise in digital technology and smartphones, students are more prone to experiencing high cognitive load, which can reduce academic success.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In the late 1980s, educational psychologist John Sweller developed cognitive load theory out of a study of problem solving, in order "to provide guidelines intended to assist in the presentation of information in a manner that encourages learner activities that optimize intellectual performance".
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Sweller's theory employs aspects of information processing theory to emphasize the inherent limitations of concurrent working memory load on learning during instruction.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] It makes use of the schema as primary unit of analysis for the design of instructional materials.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The history of cognitive load theory can be traced to the beginning of cognitive science in the 1950s and the work of G.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In his classic paper, Miller was perhaps the first to suggest that human working memory capacity has inherent limits.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] His experimental results suggested that humans are generally able to hold only seven plus or minus two units of information in short-term memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In 1973 Simon and Chase were the first to use the term *chunk* to describe how people might organize information in short-term memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This chunking of memory components has also been described as schema construction.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In the late 1980s Sweller developed cognitive load theory (CLT) while studying problem solving.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Studying learners as they solved problems, he and his associates found that learners often use a problem-solving strategy called means–ends analysis.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] He suggests problem solving by means–ends analysis requires a relatively large amount of cognitive processing capacity, which may not be devoted to schema construction.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Sweller suggested that instructional designers should prevent this unnecessary cognitive load by designing instructional materials which do not involve problem solving.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Examples of alternative instructional materials include what are known as worked examples and goal-free problems.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In the 1990s, cognitive load theory was applied in several contexts.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The empirical results from these studies led to the demonstration of several learning effects: the completion-problem effect; modality effect; split-attention effect; worked-example effect; and expertise reversal effect.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Cognitive load theory provides a general framework with broad implications for instructional design by focusing on the limitations of human working memory as a central constraint on learning.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The primary aim of the theory is to guide the effective use of this limited cognitive resource by structuring learning conditions and instructional materials in ways that reduce extraneous cognitive load and optimize intrinsic cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] By doing so, instructional designers can better direct learners' attention toward essential information and processes that support schema construction, thereby increasing germane cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Cognitive load theory distinguishes among three types of cognitive load: intrinsic, extraneous, and germane cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Intrinsic cognitive load is the inherent level of difficulty associated with a specific instructional topic.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The term was first used in the early 1990s by Chandler and Sweller.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] According to them, all instructions have an inherent difficulty associated with them (e.g., the calculation of 2 + 2, versus solving a differential equation).
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This inherent difficulty may not be altered by an instructor.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] However, many schemas may be broken into individual "subschemas" and taught in isolation, to be later brought back together and described as a combined whole.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Extraneous cognitive load is generated by the manner in which information is presented to learners and is under the control of instructional designers.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This load can be attributed to the design of the instructional materials.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Because there is a single limited cognitive resource using resources to process the extraneous load, the number of resources available to process the intrinsic load and germane load (i.e., learning) is reduced.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Thus, especially when intrinsic and/or germane load is high (i.e., when a problem is difficult), materials should be designed so as to reduce the extraneous load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] An example of extraneous cognitive load occurs when there are two possible ways to describe a square to a student.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] A square is a figure and should be described using a figural medium.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Certainly an instructor can describe a square in a verbal medium, but it takes just a second and far less effort to see what the instructor is talking about when a learner is shown a square, rather than having one described verbally.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In this instance, the efficiency of the visual medium is preferred.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This is because it does not unduly load the learner with unnecessary information.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This unnecessary cognitive load is described as extraneous.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Chandler and Sweller introduced the concept of extraneous cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This article was written to report the results of six experiments that they conducted to investigate this working memory load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Many of these experiments involved materials demonstrating the split attention effect.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] They found that the format of instructional materials either promoted or limited learning.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] They proposed that differences in performance were due to higher levels of the cognitive load imposed by the format of instruction.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] *Extraneous cognitive load* is a term for this unnecessary (artificially induced) cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Extraneous cognitive load may have different components, such as the clarity of texts or interactive demands of educational software.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As of 1993 Paas and Van Merriënboer had developed a construct known as relative condition efficiency, which helps researchers measure perceived mental effort, an index of cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This construct provides a relatively simple means of comparing instructional conditions, taking into account both mental effort ratings and performance scores.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Relative condition efficiency is calculated by subtracting standardized mental effort from standardized performance and dividing by the square root of two.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Paas and Van Merriënboer used relative condition efficiency to compare three instructional conditions (worked examples, completion problems, and discovery practice).
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] They found learners who studied worked examples were the most efficient, followed by those who used the problem completion strategy.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Since this early study many other researchers have used this and other constructs to measure cognitive load as it relates to learning and instruction.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The ergonomic approach seeks a quantitative neurophysiological expression of cognitive load which can be measured using common instruments, for example using the heart rate-blood pressure product (RPP) as a measure of both cognitive and physical occupational workload.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] They believe that it may be possible to use RPP measures to set limits on workloads and for establishing work allowance.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] There is active research interest in using physiological responses to indirectly estimate cognitive load, particularly by monitoring pupil diameter, eye gaze, respiratory rate, heart rate, or other factors.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] While some studies have found correlations between physiological factors and cognitive load, the findings have not held outside controlled laboratory environments.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Task-invoked pupillary response is one such physiological response of cognitive load on working memory, with studies finding that pupil dilation occurs with high cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Some researchers have compared different measures of cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] For example, Deleeuw and Mayer (2008) compared three commonly used measures of cognitive load and found that they responded in different ways to extraneous, intrinsic, and germane load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] A 2020 study showed that there may be various demand components that together form extraneous cognitive load, but that may need to be measured using different questionnaires.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Some research suggests that cognitive load theory has "Additivity hypothesis", which indicates that the three separate types of cognitive load may overlap.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This would mean that cognitive load theory would need a clearer distinction between types of cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] A heavy cognitive load typically creates error or some kind of interference in the task at hand.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] A heavy cognitive load can also increase stereotyping.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This is because a heavy cognitive load pushes excess information into subconscious processing, which involves the use of schemas, the patterns of thought and behavior that help to organize information into categories and identify the relationships between them.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Stereotypical associations may be automatically activated by the use of pattern recognition and schemas, producing an implicit stereotype effect.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Stereotyping is an extension of the fundamental attribution error, which also increases in frequency with heavier cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The notions of cognitive load and arousal contribute to the overload hypothesis explanation of social facilitation: in the presence of an audience, subjects tend to perform worse in subjectively complex tasks (whereas they tend to excel in subjectively easy tasks).
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The internet has transformed how individuals process, store, and retrieve information, serving both as a cognitive aid and a potential burden on working memory.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] While digital tools can reduce cognitive strain by offloading memory demands onto external systems, they also introduce challenges such as information overload, decision fatigue, and attention fragmentation.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] These multifaceted effects necessitate a nuanced understanding of the internet's impact on cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] One prominent phenomenon illustrating this impact is the Google effect, also known as digital amnesia.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This term describes the tendency to forget information readily available online, as individuals are less inclined to remember details they can easily access through search engines.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This reliance on external digital storage aligns with transactive memory theory, wherein people distribute knowledge within a group, focusing on who knows what rather than retaining all information individually.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The internet extends this system, allowing vast data storage externally and emphasizing retrieval over internal recall.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] While this can free up working memory for complex problem solving, it may also diminish long-term retention and comprehension.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Studies have shown that when individuals expect information to be accessible online, they are less likely to deeply encode it, prioritizing access over understanding.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Beyond memory offloading, digital tools enhance cognitive efficiency by simplifying complex tasks.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Well-designed digital environments can enhance knowledge acquisition by minimizing unnecessary processing demands, allowing learners to focus on essential concepts.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Features like auto-complete functions, digital calculators, and grammar-checking tools further streamline tasks, reducing the mental effort required for routine operations.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] These advantages demonstrate how, when effectively leveraged, the internet can optimize information processing and retrieval, thereby enhancing cognitive efficiency.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] However, the internet also presents significant cognitive challenges.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] One major issue is information overload, where the vast amount of available content overwhelms cognitive capacity, leading to decision fatigue and reduced learning efficiency.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The necessity of filtering through extensive information to assess credibility and relevance adds an extraneous cognitive burden, potentially diminishing focus on core learning objectives.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Research indicates that excessive information can impair decision-making by increasing cognitive effort, resulting in less effective knowledge retention.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Additionally, the prevalence of hyperlinked texts, advertisements, and continuous updates contributes to fragmented attention, making sustained, deep learning more difficult.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Another concern is the impact of media multitasking on cognitive function.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Many individuals frequently switch between multiple online streams—checking emails, browsing social media, and engaging with various digital content sources simultaneously.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] While this behavior may seem productive, studies suggest that heavy media multitasking is associated with reduced working memory efficiency, diminished attentional control, and increased distractibility.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The rapid alternation between tasks prevents sustained focus, leading to shallow information processing rather than deep comprehension.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Neuroimaging research has shown that frequent multitaskers exhibit decreased activation in brain regions associated with sustained attention and impulse control, indicating that digital environments can fragment cognitive resources.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Furthermore, the internet may alter how individuals value and interact with knowledge.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In traditional learning environments, effortful cognitive processing contributes to deeper retention and understanding.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] However, the instant accessibility of online information can create an illusion of knowledge, where individuals overestimate their understanding simply because they can quickly look up answers.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This reliance on digital search engines can lead to a false sense of expertise, as users mistake access to information for actual comprehension.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] This shift in cognitive processing raises questions about how the internet may reshape intellectual engagement, particularly in academic and professional settings where deep learning and critical thinking are essential.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] One domain where the effect of the internet may have adverse consequences for both cognitive performance and brain health is spatial navigation.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As part of their training, London taxi-drivers need to memorize and navigate through the city's complex streets, leading to structural changes in the size of a key brain region associated with memory consolidation, the hippocampus.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] More recent studies suggest such enlargement may provide protection against age-related dementia.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As a result, an over-reliance on GPS systems in apps like Google Maps, which dispense with the need for remembering routes and spatial reasoning, may also suppress brain plasticity for spatial navigation and its beneficial health effects.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] While cognitive offloading and digital tools offer clear advantages, the long-term consequences of internet reliance remain an active area of research.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The challenge lies in balancing the use of digital aids to enhance cognitive efficiency with ensuring that such reliance does not compromise memory retention, critical thinking, attentional control, and even brain health.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As digital environments continue to evolve, researchers emphasize the need for strategies that optimize cognitive load management, such as designing educational interfaces that promote deep learning while minimizing distractions.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Further investigation is needed to determine best practices for integrating digital tools into learning contexts without exacerbating the cognitive drawbacks associated with information overload and media multitasking.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] A growing body of evidence also suggests that AI may have a uniquely harmful effect on our cognition.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In the realm of education, productive struggle requiring the use of our working and long-term memory systems among others is considered "desirable difficulty" and facilitates improved cognitive performance.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Similarly, in healthcare, regularly applying skills ensures their retention and proficiency, as illustrated by a study showing poorer surgical outcomes among physicians, or deskilling, when their AI tool was discontinued.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As of 1984 it was established, for example, that there are individual differences in processing capacities between novices and experts.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Experts have more knowledge or experience with regard to a specific task which reduces the cognitive load associated with the task.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Novices do not have this experience or knowledge and thus have heavier cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] We also see structural differences in long-term memory as reflected in the London taxi driver studies cited above.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The danger of heavy cognitive load is seen in the elderly population.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Aging can cause declines in the efficiency of working memory which can contribute to higher cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Heavy cognitive load can disturb balance in elderly people.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The relationship between heavy cognitive load and control of center of mass are heavily correlated in the elderly population.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As cognitive load increases, the sway in center of mass in elderly individuals increases.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] A 2007 study examined the relationship between body sway and cognitive function and their relationship during multitasking and found disturbances in balance led to a decrease in performance on the cognitive task.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Conversely, an increasing demand for balance can increase cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As of 2014, an increasing cognitive load for students using a laptop in school has become a concern.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] With the use of Facebook and other social forms of communication, adding multiple tasks jeopardizes students' performance in the classroom.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] When many cognitive resources are available, the probability of switching from one task to another is high and does not lead to optimal switching behavior.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In a study from 2013, both students who were heavy Facebook users and students who sat nearby those who were heavy Facebook users performed poorly and resulted in lower GPA.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In 2004, British psychologists, Alan Baddeley and Graham Hitch proposed that the components of working memory are in place at six years of age.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] They found a clear difference between adult and child knowledge.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] These differences were due to developmental increases in processing efficiency.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Children lack general knowledge, and this is what creates increased cognitive load in children.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Children in impoverished families often experience even higher cognitive load in learning environments than those in middle-class families.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] These children do not hear, talk, or learn about schooling concepts because their parents often do not have formal education.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] When it comes to learning, their lack of experience with numbers, words, and concepts increases their cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As children grow older they develop superior basic processes and capacities.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] They also develop metacognition, which helps them to understand their own cognitive activities.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Lastly, they gain greater content knowledge through their experiences.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] These elements help reduce cognitive load in children as they develop.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Gesturing is a technique children use to reduce cognitive load while speaking.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] By gesturing, they can free up working memory for other tasks.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Pointing allows a child to use the object they are pointing at as the best representation of it, which means they do not have to hold this representation in their working memory, thereby reducing their cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Additionally, gesturing about an object that is absent reduces the difficulty of having to picture it in their mind.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As of 2013 it has been theorized that an impoverished environment can contribute to cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Regardless of the task at hand, or the processes used in solving the task, people who experience poverty also experience higher cognitive load.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] A number of factors contribute to the cognitive load in people with lower socioeconomic status that are not present in middle and upper-class people.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Bodily activity can both be advantageous and detrimental to learning depending on how this activity is implemented.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] Cognitive load theorists have asked for updates that makes CLT more compatible with insights from embodied cognition research.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] As a result, embodied cognitive load theory has been suggested as a means to predict the usefulness of interactive features in learning environments.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In this framework, the benefits of an interactive feature (such as easier cognitive processing) need to exceed its cognitive costs (such as motor coordination) in order for an embodied mode of interaction to increase learning outcomes.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] With increase in secondary tasks inside the cockpit, cognitive load estimation has become an important problem for both automotive drivers and pilots.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] The issue has been addressed with various features such as drowsiness detection.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] For automotive drivers, researchers have explored various physiological parameters like heart rate, facial expression, and ocular parameters.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] In aviation there are numerous simulation studies on analysing pilots' distraction and attention using various physiological parameters.
[src:platform-engineering/cognitive-load] For military fast jet pilots, researchers have explored air-to-ground dive attacks and recorded cardiac, EEG and ocular parameters.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:platform-engineering/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:platform-engineering/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:platform-engineering/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] A software engineer applies a software development process to define, implement, test, manage, and maintain software systems.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Beginning in the 1960s, software engineering was recognized as a separate field of engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The development of software engineering was seen as a struggle.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Problems included software that was over budget, exceeded deadlines, required extensive debugging and maintenance, and unsuccessfully met the needs of consumers or was never even completed.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In 1968, NATO organized the first conference on software engineering, which addressed emerging challenges in software development and played a key role in formalizing guidelines and best practices for creating reliable and maintainable software.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Modern, generally accepted best practices for software engineering have been collected by the ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 7 subcommittee and published as the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge (SWEBOK).
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software engineering is considered one of the major computing disciplines.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In modern systems, where concepts such as Edge Computing, Internet of Things and Cyber-physical Systems are prevalent, software is a critical factor.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Thus, software engineering is closely related to the systems engineering discipline.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The origins of the term *software engineering* have been attributed to various sources.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The term appeared in a list of services offered by companies in the June 1965 issue of "Computers and Automation" and was used more formally in the August 1966 issue of *Communications of the ACM* (Volume 9, number 8) in "President's Letter to the ACM Membership" by Anthony A.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] It is also associated with the title of a NATO conference in 1968 by Professor Friedrich L.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Margaret Hamilton described the discipline of "software engineering" during the Apollo missions to give what they were doing legitimacy.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] At the time, there was perceived to be a "software crisis".
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The 40th International Conference on Software Engineering (ICSE 2018) celebrated 50 years of "Software Engineering" with the Plenary Sessions' keynotes of Frederick Brooks and Margaret Hamilton.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In 1984, the Software Engineering Institute (SEI) was established as a federally funded research and development center headquartered on the campus of Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, United States.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Watts Humphrey founded the SEI Software Process Program, aimed at understanding and managing the software engineering process.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The Process Maturity Levels introduced became the Capability Maturity Model Integration for Development (CMMI-DEV), which defined how the US Government evaluates the abilities of a software development team.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Individual commentators have disagreed sharply on how to define *software engineering* or its legitimacy as an engineering discipline.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] David Parnas has said that software engineering is, in fact, a form of engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Steve McConnell has said that it is not, but that it should be.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Donald Knuth has said that programming is an art and a science.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Dijkstra claimed that the terms *software engineering* and *software engineer* have been misused in the United States.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Requirements engineering is about elicitation, analysis, specification, and validation of requirements for software.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software requirements can be functional, non-functional or domain.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Functional requirements describe expected behaviors (i.e. outputs).
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Non-functional requirements specify issues like portability, security, maintainability, reliability, scalability, performance, reusability, and flexibility.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] They are classified into the following types: interface constraints, performance constraints (such as response time, security, storage space, etc.), operating constraints, life cycle constraints (maintainability, portability, etc.), and economic constraints.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Knowledge of how the system or software works is needed when it comes to specifying non-functional requirements.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Domain requirements have to do with the characteristic of a certain category or domain of projects.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software design is the process of making high-level plans for the software.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software construction typically involves programming (a.k.a. coding), unit testing, integration testing, and debugging so as to implement the design."Software testing is related to, but different from, ... debugging".
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software testing is an empirical, technical investigation conducted to provide stakeholders with information about the quality of the software under test.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software testing can be viewed as a risk based activity.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] When described separately from construction, testing typically is performed by test engineers or quality assurance instead of the programmers who wrote it.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] It is performed at the system level and is considered an aspect of software quality.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The testers' goals during the testing process are to minimize the overall number of tests to a manageable set and make well-informed decisions regarding which risks should be prioritized for testing and which can wait.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Program analysis is the process of analyzing computer programs with respect to an aspect such as performance, robustness, and security.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software maintenance refers to supporting the software after release.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] It may include but is not limited to: error correction, optimization, deletion of unused and discarded features, and enhancement of existing features.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Usually, maintenance takes up 40% to 80% of project cost.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Knowledge of computer programming is a prerequisite for becoming a software engineer.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In 2004, the IEEE Computer Society produced the SWEBOK, which has been published as ISO/IEC Technical Report 1979:2005, describing the body of knowledge that they recommend to be mastered by a graduate software engineer with four years of experience.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Many software engineers enter the profession by obtaining a university degree or training at a vocational school.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] One standard international curriculum for undergraduate software engineering degrees was defined by the Joint Task Force on Computing Curricula of the IEEE Computer Society and the Association for Computing Machinery, and updated in 2014.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] A number of universities have Software Engineering degree programs; as of 2010, there were 244 Campus Bachelor of Software Engineering programs, 70 Online programs, 230 Masters-level programs, 41 Doctorate-level programs, and 69 Certificate-level programs in the United States.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In addition to university education, many companies sponsor internships for students wishing to pursue careers in information technology.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] These internships can introduce the student to real-world tasks that typical software engineers encounter every day.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Similar experience can be gained through military service in software engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] A small but growing number of practitioners have software engineering degrees.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In 1987, the Department of Computing at Imperial College London introduced the first three-year software engineering bachelor's degree in the world; in the following year, the University of Sheffield established a similar program.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Since then, software engineering undergraduate degrees have been established at many universities.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] A standard international curriculum for undergraduate software engineering degrees, SE2004, was defined by a steering committee between 2001 and 2004 with funding from the Association for Computing Machinery and the IEEE Computer Society.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] As of 2004, about 50 universities in the U.S. offer software engineering degrees, which teach both computer science and engineering principles and practices.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The first software engineering master's degree was established at Seattle University in 1979.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Since then, graduate software engineering degrees have been made available from many more universities.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Likewise in Canada, the Canadian Engineering Accreditation Board (CEAB) of the Canadian Council of Professional Engineers has recognized several software engineering programs.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Additionally, many online advanced degrees in Software Engineering have appeared such as the Master of Science in Software Engineering (MSE) degree offered through the Computer Science and Engineering Department at California State University, Fullerton.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Steve McConnell opines that because most universities teach computer science rather than software engineering, there is a shortage of true software engineers.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] ETS (École de technologie supérieure) University and UQAM (Université du Québec à Montréal) were mandated by IEEE to develop the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge (SWEBOK), which has become an ISO standard describing the body of knowledge covered by a software engineer.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Legal requirements for the licensing or certification of professional software engineers vary around the world.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In the UK, there is no licensing or legal requirement to assume or use the job title Software Engineer.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In some areas of Canada, such as Alberta, British Columbia, Ontario, and Quebec, software engineers can hold the Professional Engineer (P.Eng) designation and/or the Information Systems Professional (I.S.P.) designation.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In Europe, Software Engineers can obtain the European Engineer (EUR ING) professional title.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software Engineers can also become professionally qualified as a Chartered Engineer through the British Computer Society.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In the United States, the NCEES began offering a Professional Engineer exam for Software Engineering in 2013, thereby allowing Software Engineers to be licensed and recognized.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] NCEES ended the exam after April 2019 due to lack of participation.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Mandatory licensing is currently still largely debated, and perceived as controversial.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The IEEE Computer Society and the ACM, the two main US-based professional organizations of software engineering, publish guides to the profession of software engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The IEEE's *Guide to the Software Engineering Body of Knowledge – 2004 Version*, or SWEBOK, defines the field and describes the knowledge the IEEE expects a practicing software engineer to have.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The IEEE also promulgates a "Software Engineering Code of Ethics".
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] There are an estimated 26.9 million professional software engineers in the world as of 2022, up from 21 million in 2016.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Many software engineers work as employees or contractors.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software engineers work with businesses, government agencies (civilian or military), and non-profit organizations.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Some software engineers work for themselves as freelancers.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Some organizations have specialists to perform each of the tasks in the software development process.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Other organizations require software engineers to do many or all of them.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In large projects, people may specialize in only one role.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In small projects, people may fill several or all roles at the same time.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Many companies hire interns, often university or college students during a summer break, or externships.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Specializations include analysts, architects, developers, testers, technical support, middleware analysts, project managers, software product managers, educators, and researchers.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Most software engineers and programmers work 40 hours a week, but about 15 percent of software engineers and 11 percent of programmers worked more than 50 hours a week in 2008.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) counted 1,365,500 software developers holding jobs in the U.S. in 2018.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Due to its relative newness as a field of study, formal education in software engineering is often taught as part of a computer science curriculum, and many software engineers hold computer science degrees.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The BLS estimates 2024 to 2034 the growth for software engineers is 15% which is less than their prediction from 2023 to 2033 that computer software engineering would increase by 17%.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] This is down from the 2022 to 2032 BLS estimate of 25% for software engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] And, is further down from their 30% 2010 to 2020 BLS estimate.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Due to this trend, job growth may not be as fast as during the last decade, as jobs that would have gone to computer software engineers in the United States would instead be outsourced to computer software engineers in countries such as India and other foreign countries.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In addition, the BLS Job Outlook for Computer Programmers, the U.S.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) Occupational Outlook predicts a decline of -7 percent from 2016 to 2026, a further decline of -9 percent from 2019 to 2029, a decline of -10 percent from 2021 to 2031. and then a decline of -11 percent from 2022 to 2032.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Currently their prediction for 2024 to 2034 is a decline of -6 percent.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Since computer programming can be done from anywhere in the world, companies sometimes hire programmers in countries where wages are lower.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Furthermore, the ratio of women in many software fields has also been declining over the years as compared to other engineering fields.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Then there is the additional concern that recent advances in Artificial Intelligence might impact the demand for future generations of Software Engineers.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] However, this trend may change or slow in the future as many current software engineers in the U.S. market flee the profession or age out of the market in the next few decades.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The Software Engineering Institute offers certifications on specific topics like security, process improvement and software architecture.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] IBM, Microsoft and other companies also sponsor their own certification examinations.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Many IT certification programs are oriented toward specific technologies, and managed by the vendors of these technologies.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] These certification programs are tailored to the institutions that would employ people who use these technologies.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Broader certification of general software engineering skills is available through various professional societies.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] As of 2006, the IEEE had certified over 575 software professionals as a Certified Software Development Professional (CSDP).
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In 2008 they added an entry-level certification known as the Certified Software Development Associate (CSDA).
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The ACM and the IEEE Computer Society together examined the possibility of licensing of software engineers as Professional Engineers in the 1990s, but eventually decided that such licensing was inappropriate for the professional industrial practice of software engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Leveson presented a more balanced analysis of the licensing issue in 2002.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In the U.K. the British Computer Society has developed a legally recognized professional certification called *Chartered IT Professional (CITP)*, available to fully qualified members (*MBCS*).
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Software engineers may be eligible for membership of the British Computer Society or Institution of Engineering and Technology and so qualify to be considered for Chartered Engineer status through either of those institutions.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] In Canada the Canadian Information Processing Society has developed a legally recognized professional certification called *Information Systems Professional (ISP)*.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The PEO does not recognize any online or distance education however; and does not consider Computer Science programs to be equivalent to software engineering programs despite the tremendous overlap between the two.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] This has sparked controversy and a certification war.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] It has also held the number of P.Eng holders for the profession exceptionally low.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] The vast majority of working professionals in the field hold a degree in CS, not SE.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Given the difficult certification path for holders of non-SE degrees, most never bother to pursue the license.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] This approach had some flaws, mainly the distance / time zone difference that prevented human interaction between clients and developers and the massive job transfer.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] This had a negative impact on many aspects of the software engineering profession.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] For example, some students in the developed world avoid education related to software engineering because of the fear of offshore outsourcing (importing software products or services from other countries) and of being displaced by foreign visa workers.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Additionally, the glut of high-tech workers has led to a wider adoption of the 996 working hour system and ‘007’ schedules as the expected work load.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Although statistics do not currently show a threat to software engineering itself; a related career, computer programming does appear to have been affected.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Nevertheless, the ability to smartly leverage offshore and near-shore resources via the follow-the-sun workflow has improved the overall operational capability of many organizations.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] When North Americans leave work, Asians are just arriving to work.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] When Asians are leaving work, Europeans arrive to work.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] This provides a continuous ability to have human oversight on business-critical processes 24 hours per day, without paying overtime compensation or disrupting a key human resource, sleep patterns.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] While global outsourcing has several advantages, global – and generally distributed – development can run into serious difficulties resulting from the distance between developers.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] This is due to the key elements of this type of distance that have been identified as geographical, temporal, cultural and communication (that includes the use of different languages and dialects of English in different locations).
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Research has been carried out in the area of global software development over the last 15 years and an extensive body of relevant work published that highlights the benefits and problems associated with the complex activity.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] As with other aspects of software engineering research is ongoing in this and related areas.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Some call for licensing, certification and codified bodies of knowledge as mechanisms for spreading the engineering knowledge and maturing the field.
[src:platform-engineering/software-engineering] Some claim that the concept of software engineering is so new that it is rarely understood, and it is widely misinterpreted, including in software engineering textbooks, papers, and among the communities of programmers and crafters.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering deals with work processes, optimization methods, and risk management tools in such projects.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering ensures that all likely aspects of a project or system are considered and integrated into a whole.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is quite unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] A manufacturing process is focused on repetitive activities that achieve high-quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The systems engineering process must begin by discovering the real problems that need to be resolved and identifying the most probable or highest-impact failures that can occur.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering involves finding solutions to these problems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The term *systems engineering* can be traced back to Bell Telephone Laboratories in the 1940s.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The need to identify and manipulate the properties of a system as a whole, which in complex engineering projects may greatly differ from the sum of the parts' properties, motivated various industries, especially those developing systems for the U.S. military, to apply the discipline.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] When it was no longer possible to rely on design evolution to improve upon a system and the existing tools were not sufficient to meet growing demands, new methods began to be developed that addressed the complexity directly.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The continuing evolution of systems engineering comprises the development and identification of new methods and modeling techniques.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] These methods aid in a better comprehension of the design and developmental control of engineering systems as they grow more complex.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Popular tools that are often used in the systems engineering context were developed during these times, including Universal Systems Language (USL), Unified Modeling Language (UML), Quality function deployment (QFD), and Integration Definition (IDEF).
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] In 1990, a professional society for systems engineering, the *National Council on Systems Engineering* (NCOSE), was founded by representatives from a number of U.S. corporations and organizations.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] NCOSE was created to address the need for improvements in systems engineering practices and education.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] As a result of growing involvement from systems engineers outside of the U.S., the name of the organization was changed to the International Council on Systems Engineering (INCOSE) in 1995.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Schools in several countries offer graduate programs in systems engineering, and continuing education options are also available for practicing engineers.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering signifies only an approach and, more recently, a discipline in engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The aim of education in systems engineering is to formalize various approaches simply and in doing so, identify new methods and research opportunities similar to that which occurs in other fields of engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] As an approach, systems engineering is holistic and interdisciplinary in flavor.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The traditional scope of engineering embraces the conception, design, development, production, and operation of physical systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering, as originally conceived, falls within this scope.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] "Systems engineering", in this sense of the term, refers to the building of engineering concepts.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The use of the term "systems engineer" has evolved over time to embrace a wider, more holistic concept of "systems" and of engineering processes.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] This evolution of the definition has been a subject of ongoing controversy, and the term continues to apply to both the narrower and a broader scope.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Traditional systems engineering was seen as a branch of engineering in the classical sense, that is, as applied only to physical systems, such as spacecraft and aircraft.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] More recently, systems engineering has evolved to take on a broader meaning especially when humans were seen as an essential component of a system.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering focuses on analyzing and eliciting customer needs and required functionality early in the development cycle, documenting requirements, then proceeding with design synthesis and system validation while considering the complete problem, the system lifecycle.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] This includes fully understanding all of the stakeholders involved.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Depending on their application, although there are several models that are used in the industry, all of them aim to identify the relation between the various stages mentioned above and incorporate feedback.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Examples of such models include the Waterfall model and the VEE model (also called the V model).
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] System development often requires contribution from diverse technical disciplines.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] By providing a systems (holistic) view of the development effort, systems engineering helps mold all the technical contributors into a unified team effort, forming a structured development process that proceeds from concept to production to operation and, in some cases, to termination and disposal.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] In an acquisition, the holistic integrative discipline combines contributions and balances tradeoffs among cost, schedule, and performance while maintaining an acceptable level of risk covering the entire life cycle of the item.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] This perspective is often replicated in educational programs, in that systems engineering courses are taught by faculty from other engineering departments, which helps create an interdisciplinary environment.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The need for systems engineering arose with the increase in complexity of systems and projects, in turn exponentially increasing the possibility of component friction, and therefore the unreliability of the design.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] When speaking in this context, complexity incorporates not only engineering systems but also the logical human organization of data.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] At the same time, a system can become more complex due to an increase in size as well as with an increase in the amount of data, variables, or the number of fields that are involved in the design.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The International Space Station is an example of such a system.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The development of smarter control algorithms, microprocessor design, and analysis of environmental systems also come within the purview of systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering encourages the use of tools and methods to better comprehend and manage complexity in systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Taking an interdisciplinary approach to engineering systems is inherently complex since the behavior of and interaction among system components is not always immediately well defined or understood.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Defining and characterizing such systems and subsystems and the interactions among them is one of the goals of systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] In doing so, the gap that exists between informal requirements from users, operators, marketing organizations, and technical specifications is successfully bridged.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The principles of systems engineering – holism, emergent behavior, boundary, et al. – can be applied to any system, complex or otherwise, provided systems thinking is employed at all levels.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Besides defense and aerospace, many information and technology-based companies, software development firms, and industries in the field of electronics & communications require systems engineers as part of their team.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] An analysis by the INCOSE Systems Engineering Center of Excellence (SECOE) indicates that optimal effort spent on systems engineering is about 15–20% of the total project effort.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] At the same time, studies have shown that systems engineering essentially leads to a reduction in costs among other benefits.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] However, no quantitative survey at a larger scale encompassing a wide variety of industries has been conducted until recently.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Such studies are underway to determine the effectiveness and quantify the benefits of systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering encourages the use of modeling and simulation to validate assumptions or theories on systems and the interactions within them.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Use of methods that allow early detection of possible failures, in safety engineering, are integrated into the design process.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] At the same time, decisions made at the beginning of a project whose consequences are not clearly understood can have enormous implications later in the life of a system, and it is the task of the modern systems engineer to explore these issues and make critical decisions.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] No method guarantees today's decisions will still be valid when a system goes into service years or decades after first conceived.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] However, there are techniques that support the process of systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Examples include soft systems methodology, Jay Wright Forrester's System dynamics method, and the Unified Modeling Language (UML)—all currently being explored, evaluated, and developed to support the engineering decision process.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Undergraduate university programs explicitly in systems engineering are growing in number but remain uncommon, the degrees including such material are most often presented as a BS in Industrial Engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Typically programs (either by themselves or in combination with interdisciplinary study) are offered beginning at the graduate level in both academic and professional tracks, resulting in the grant of either a MS/MEng or Ph.D./EngD degree.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] INCOSE, in collaboration with the Systems Engineering Research Center at Stevens Institute of Technology maintains a regularly updated directory of worldwide academic programs at suitably accredited institutions.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] As of 2017, it lists over 140 universities in North America offering more than 400 undergraduate and graduate programs in systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Widespread institutional acknowledgment of the field as a distinct subdiscipline is quite recent; the 2009 edition of the same publication reported the number of such schools and programs at only 80 and 165, respectively.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Both of these patterns strive to educate the systems engineer who is able to oversee interdisciplinary projects with the depth required of a core engineer.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering tools are strategies, procedures, and techniques that aid in performing systems engineering on a project or product.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The purpose of these tools varies from database management, graphical browsing, simulation, and reasoning, to document production, neutral import/export, and more.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] There are many definitions of what a system is in the field of systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering processes encompass all creative, manual, and technical activities necessary to define the product and which need to be carried out to convert a system definition to a sufficiently detailed system design specification for product manufacture and deployment.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Models play important and diverse roles in systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Together, these definitions are broad enough to encompass physical engineering models used in the verification of a system design, as well as schematic models like a functional flow block diagram and mathematical (i.e. quantitative) models used in the trade study process.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The main reason for using mathematical models and diagrams in trade studies is to provide estimates of system effectiveness, performance or technical attributes, and cost from a set of known or estimable quantities.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Typically, a collection of separate models is needed to provide all of these outcome variables.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The heart of any mathematical model is a set of meaningful quantitative relationships among its inputs and outputs.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] These relationships can be as simple as adding up constituent quantities to obtain a total, or as complex as a set of differential equations describing the trajectory of a spacecraft in a gravitational field.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Ideally, the relationships express causality, not just correlation.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Furthermore, key to successful systems engineering activities are also the methods with which these models are efficiently and effectively managed and used to simulate the systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] However, diverse domains often present recurring problems of modeling and simulation for systems engineering, and new advancements are aiming to cross-fertilize methods among distinct scientific and engineering communities, under the title of 'Modeling & Simulation-based Systems Engineering'.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Initially, when the primary purpose of a systems engineer is to comprehend a complex problem, graphic representations of a system are used to communicate a system's functional and data requirements.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] A graphical representation relates the various subsystems or parts of a system through functions, data, or interfaces.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Any or each of the above methods is used in an industry based on its requirements.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] For instance, the N2 chart may be used where interfaces between systems are important.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Part of the design phase is to create structural and behavioral models of the system.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Once the requirements are understood, it is now the responsibility of a systems engineer to refine them and to determine, along with other engineers, the best technology for a job.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] At this point starting with a trade study, systems engineering encourages the use of weighted choices to determine the best option.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] A decision matrix, or Pugh method, is one way (QFD is another) to make this choice while considering all criteria that are important.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The trade study in turn informs the design, which again affects graphic representations of the system (without changing the requirements).
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] In an SE process, this stage represents the iterative step that is carried out until a feasible solution is found.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] A decision matrix is often populated using techniques such as statistical analysis, reliability analysis, system dynamics (feedback control), and optimization methods.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems Modeling Language (SysML), a modeling language used for systems engineering applications, supports the specification, analysis, design, verification and validation of a broad range of complex systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Lifecycle Modeling Language (LML), is an open-standard modeling language designed for systems engineering that supports the full lifecycle: conceptual, utilization, support, and retirement stages.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Many related fields may be considered tightly coupled to systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Cognitive systems engineering (CSE) is a specific approach to the description and analysis of human-machine systems or sociotechnical systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The three main themes of CSE are how humans cope with complexity, how work is accomplished by the use of artifacts, and how human-machine systems and socio-technical systems can be described as joint cognitive systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] CSE has since its beginning become a recognized scientific discipline, sometimes also referred to as cognitive engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The concept of a Joint Cognitive System (JCS) has in particular become widely used as a way of understanding how complex socio-technical systems can be described with varying degrees of resolution.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The more than 20 years of experience with CSE has been described extensively.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Like systems engineering, configuration management as practiced in the defense and aerospace industry is a broad systems-level practice.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Control engineering and its design and implementation of control systems, used extensively in nearly every industry, is a large sub-field of systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The cruise control on an automobile and the guidance system for a ballistic missile are two examples.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Control systems theory is an active field of applied mathematics involving the investigation of solution spaces and the development of new methods for the analysis of the control process.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Industrial engineering is a branch of engineering that concerns the development, improvement, implementation, and evaluation of integrated systems of people, money, knowledge, information, equipment, energy, material, and process.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Industrial engineering draws upon the principles and methods of engineering analysis and synthesis, as well as mathematical, physical, and social sciences together with the principles and methods of engineering analysis and design to specify, predict, and evaluate results obtained from such systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Production Systems Engineering (PSE) is an emerging branch of Engineering intended to uncover fundamental principles of production systems and utilize them for analysis, continuous improvement, and design.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Interface design and its specification are concerned with assuring that the pieces of a system connect and inter-operate with other parts of the system and with external systems as necessary.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Interface design also includes assuring that system interfaces are able to accept new features, including mechanical, electrical, and logical interfaces, including reserved wires, plug-space, command codes, and bits in communication protocols.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Human-Computer Interaction (HCI) or Human-Machine Interface (HMI) is another aspect of interface design and is a critical aspect of modern systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems engineering principles are applied in the design of communication protocols for local area networks and wide area networks.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Mechatronic engineering, like systems engineering, is a multidisciplinary field of engineering that uses dynamic systems modeling to express tangible constructs.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] In that regard, it is almost indistinguishable from Systems Engineering, but what sets it apart is the focus on smaller details rather than larger generalizations and relationships.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] As such, both fields are distinguished by the scope of their projects rather than the methodology of their practice.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Operations research supports systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Operations research, briefly, is concerned with the optimization of a process under multiple constraints.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Performance engineering is the discipline of ensuring a system meets customer expectations for performance throughout its life.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Performance is usually defined as the speed with which a certain operation is executed or the capability of executing a number of such operations in a unit of time.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Performance may be degraded when operations queued to execute are throttled by limited system capacity.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] For example, the performance of a packet-switched network is characterized by the end-to-end packet transit delay or the number of packets switched in an hour.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The design of high-performance systems uses analytical or simulation modeling, whereas the delivery of high-performance implementation involves thorough performance testing.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Performance engineering relies heavily on statistics, queueing theory, and probability theory for its tools and processes.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Program management (or project management) has many similarities with systems engineering, but has broader-based origins than the engineering ones of systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Project management is also closely related to both program management and systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Both include scheduling as an engineering support tool in assessing interdisciplinary concerns under the management process.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] In particular, the direct relationship of resources, performance features, and risk to the duration of a task or the dependency links among tasks and impacts across the system lifecycle are systems engineering concerns.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Proposal engineering is the application of scientific and mathematical principles to design, construct, and operate a cost-effective proposal development system.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Basically, proposal engineering uses the "systems engineering process" to create a cost-effective proposal and increase the odds of a successful proposal.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Reliability engineering is the discipline of ensuring a system meets customer expectations for reliability throughout its life (i.e., it does not fail more frequently than expected).
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Next to the prediction of failure, it is just as much about the prevention of failure.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Reliability engineering applies to all aspects of the system.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] It is closely associated with maintainability, availability (dependability or RAMS preferred by some), and integrated logistics support.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Reliability engineering is always a critical component of safety engineering, as in failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA) and hazard fault tree analysis, and of security engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Risk management, the practice of assessing and dealing with risk is one of the interdisciplinary parts of Systems Engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Systems Engineering has Risk Management define, tailor, implement, and monitor a structured process for risk management which is integrated into the overall effort.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The techniques of safety engineering may be applied by non-specialist engineers in designing complex systems to minimize the probability of safety-critical failures.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The "System Safety Engineering" function helps to identify "safety hazards" in emerging designs and may assist with techniques to "mitigate" the effects of (potentially) hazardous conditions that cannot be designed out of systems.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] Security engineering can be viewed as an interdisciplinary field that integrates the community of practice for control systems design, reliability, safety, and systems engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] It may involve such sub-specialties as authentication of system users, system targets, and others: people, objects, and processes.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] From its beginnings, software engineering has helped shape modern systems engineering practice.
[src:platform-engineering/systems-engineering] The techniques used in the handling of the complexities of large software-intensive systems have had a major effect on the shaping and reshaping of the tools, methods, and processes of Systems Engineering.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Platform engineering is the discipline of designing and building toolchains and workflows that enable self-service capabilities for software engineering organizations in the cloud-native era.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Platform engineers provide an integrated product most often referred to as an “Internal Developer Platform” covering the operational necessities of the entire lifecycle of an application.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] An Internal Developer Platform (IDP) encompasses a variety of technologies and tools, integrated in a manner that reduces cognitive load on developers while retaining essential context and underlying technologies.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] It helps operations structure their setup and enable developer self-service.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Platform engineering done right means providing golden paths and paved roads that match the preferred abstraction level of the individual developer, who interacts with the IDP.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] In this article we are going to explore the origins of this discipline and discuss the main focus areas of platform engineers.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] We will also explain how this fits into the setup of a modern engineering organization and is actually a key component in most advanced development teams.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Let’s turn the clock back a couple of decades.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The late 90s and early 2000s, the time most setups had a single gatekeeper (and point of failure), the SysAdmin.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] If developers wanted to get anything done to run their applications, they had to go through them.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] In practice, this translated to the well-known “throw over the fence” workflow, which led to poor experiences on both sides of the fence.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] As an industry, we all agreed this was not the ideal we should aspire to.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] At the same time that cloud started becoming a thing, with AWS launching in 2006, the concept of DevOps gained ground and established itself as the new golden standard for engineering teams.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] While cloud native drove huge improvements in areas like scalability, availability and operability, it also meant setups became a lot more complex.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Gone were the days of running a single script to deploy a monolithic application consuming one relational database.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Suddenly, engineers had to master 10 different tools, Helm charts, Terraform modules, etc. just to deploy and test a simple code change to one of multiple environments in your multi-cluster microservice setup.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The problem is that throughout this toolchain evolution, the industry seemingly decided that division of labor (Ops and Devs), which proved successful in virtually every other sector of the global economy, was not a good idea.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Instead, the DevOps paradigm was championed as the way to achieve a high performing setup.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The issue with this approach is that for most companies, this is actually rather unrealistic.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] While the above works for very advanced organizations like Google, Amazon or Airbnb, it is very far from trivial to replicate true DevOps in practice for most other teams.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The main reason being it is unlikely most companies have access to the same talent pool and the same level of resources they can invest into just optimizing their developer workflows and experience.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Instead, what tends to happen when a regular engineering organization tries to implement true DevOps, is that a series of antipatterns emerge.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] This is well documented by the Team Topologies team (Matthew Skelton and Manuel Pais, speaker at one of our Platform Engineers meetups) in their analysis of DevOps anti-types, a highly recommended read for anyone who wants to better understand these dynamics.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Below, an example of what emerges in many development teams when the organization decides to implement DevOps and remove a formal Ops role or team.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Developers (usually the more senior ones) end up taking responsibility for managing environments, infrastructure, etc.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] This leads to a setup where “shadow operations” are performed by the same engineers whose input in terms of coding and product development is most valuable.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The senior engineer who now becomes responsible for the setup and needs to solve requests from more junior colleagues.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The wider organization, which is now misusing some of its most expensive and talented resources and cannot ship features with the same speed and reliability.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] This type of antipatterns has been shown by a number of studies, such as the State of DevOps by Puppet or, most recently, by Humanitec’s Benchmarking study.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] In the latter, top and low performing organizations were clustered, based on standard DevOps metrics (lead time, deployment frequency, MTTR, etc.).
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] As shown below, a stunning 44% of low performing organizations experience the above antipattern, with some developers doing DevOps tasks on their own and helping less experienced colleagues.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] This is compared to top performers, where 100% of the organizations have successfully implemented a true “you build it, you run it” approach.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] So what is the key difference between low and top performing organizations?
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] How do the best teams ensure their developers can run their apps and services, without the constant need for help by senior colleagues?
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] You guessed it, they have a platform team building an Internal Developer Platform.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The State of DevOps Report 2020 by Puppet clearly shows the correlation between the use of internal platforms and the degree of DevOps evolution of organizations.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] That is what the best engineering organizations do.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] They set up internal platform teams who build IDPs.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] When using these IDPs, developers can pick the right level of abstraction to run their apps and services, depending on their preference, i.e. do they like messing around with Helm charts, YAML files and Terraform modules?
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Are they a junior frontend who doesn’t care if the app is running on EKS?
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Fantastic, they can just self-serve an environment that comes fully provisioned with everything they need to deploy and test their code, without worrying where it runs.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] What do we mean by golden paths and paved roads?
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Today, most CI/CD setups are focused on simply updating images.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] CI builds them, updates the image path in configs, done.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] That covers most of the deployment use cases.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Platform engineering is about binding all of this into a paved road.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Rather than letting everybody operate everything and having to understand the entire toolchain to do so, platform engineers provide the glue to bind everything into a consistent self-service experience.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] In the words of Evan Bottcher (Thoughtworks), platforms are “a foundation of self-service APIs, tools, services, knowledge and support, which are arranged as a compelling internal product.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Many organizations are waking up to the benefits of Internal Developer Platforms and developer self-service.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Hiring the right talent to build such platforms and workflows though can be tricky.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] And even trickier is to ensure they consistently deliver a reliable product to the rest of the engineering organization, incorporating their feedback into the IDP.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The platform team needs a clear mission.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] An example: “Build reliable workflows that allow engineers to independently interact with our setup and self-serve the infrastructure they need to run their apps and services”.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Whatever makes the most sense for your team, make sure this is defined from the get go.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] It is also extremely important to establish a clear role for the platform team, which shouldn’t be seen as yet another help desk that spins up environments on demand, but rather as a dedicated product team serving internal customers.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Expanding on the product focus, the platform team needs to be driven by a product mindset.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] They need to focus on what provides real value to their internal customers, the app developers, based on the feedback they gave them.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Make sure they ship features based on this feedback loop and don’t get distracted by playing around with a shiny new technology that just came out.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Platform teams prevent other teams within from reinventing the wheel by tackling shared problems over and over.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] It’s key to figure out what these common issues are: start by understanding developer pain points and friction areas that cause slowdowns in development.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] This information can be gathered both qualitatively through developers’ feedback and quantitatively, looking at engineering KPIs.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Often platform teams are seen as a pure cost center, because they don’t ship any actual product features for the end user.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] They are only glueing together our systems after all.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] This is a very dangerous perspective and, of course, that glue is extremely valuable.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Platform engineers need to embrace and advertise themselves and their value proposition internally.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Once you have designed the golden paths and paved roads for your teams, the main value you create as a platform team is to be the sticky glue that brings the toolchain together and ensures a smooth self-service workflow for your engineers.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] The same way platform teams should prevent other teams within the organization from reinventing the wheel and finding new creative solutions to the same problems, they should avoid falling into the same fallacy.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] It doesn’t matter if your homegrown CI/CD solution is superior today, commercial vendors will catch up eventually.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Platform teams should always ask what is their differentiator.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Instead of building in-house alternatives to a CI system or a metrics dashboard and compete against businesses that have 20 or 50 times their capacity, they should focus on the specific needs of their organization and tailor off-the-shelf solutions to their requirements.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Commercial competitors are more likely to optimize for more generic needs of the industry anyway.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] According to Puppet’s State of DevOps Report 2021, “highly evolved organizations tend to follow the Team Topologies model”.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Published in 2019, the book Team Topologies by Matthew Skelton and Manuel Pais became one of the most influential blueprints for modern team setups in successful engineering organisations.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] According to their blueprint, there are four fundamental topologies teams should structure themselves around.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] As painted in the graphic above, the platform team is transversal to all others, ensuring a smooth self-service workflow, from code to production.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] A common misconception is that platform engineering is something that only makes sense in large teams.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] And while if your team is composed of 5 developers, a platform team and IDP are surely an overkill, as soon as your organization grows past the 20-30 developers mark, an Internal Developer Platform is probably something you should look at, sooner rather than later.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] I have heard countless stories of teams who delayed building an IDP for way too long and had to suffer unnecessary hardships, e.g. your only DevOps hire leaves and your whole organization can’t deploy for weeks.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] IDPs and hiring platform engineers are investments you might want to consider today.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] If you are reading this, you are already halfway there.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Attend our events, join the Slack channel, engage with other platform engineers and platform nerds.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Follow the journey of other teams, such as Adevinta, Flywire and others.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Share with the community what your team struggles with and understand when and where self-service might make sense.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Check out existing offerings around Internal Developer Platforms to jumpstart your journey.
[src:platform-engineering/what-is-platform-engineering] Start lightweight and keep iterating on use-cases.
